<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4812&amp;p=44287#p44287</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4812&amp;p=44287#p44287"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[NESASM .db rows limited to 24 bytes per line. Why?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4812&amp;p=44287#p44287"><![CDATA[
The main reason i prefer anything beside NESASM is the banking system that is meant to be used for PCEngine (TG-16)  development.<br /><br />You see, despite the name, NESASM is just a modified assembler for the TurboGrafx-16.<br /><br />Obviously there is no reason to completely slight the program, but it wont run in a 64bit environment.<br /><br />I prefer ASM6. It has all the features of the more robust 6502 assemblers (like unnamed labels,) is open source (no OS limitations,) and allows some neat tricks (like embedding the header into the project, and .including the Sprite and background tiles onto the end, instead of concatenating the files.)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3524">Compton</a> — Sat Mar 14, 2009 9:16 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
